One test failed - `DeleteConfirmed_InvalidId_RedirectsWithError`. The issue is that when `Find(999)` returns null, the controller code tries to access `student.FirstMidName` on line 213, which throws a NullReferenceException. The catch block on line 222 catches `Exception` (not `NullReferenceException` specifically). Wait, let me re-read:

```csharp
public ActionResult DeleteConfirmed(int id)
{
    try
    {
        Student student = db.Students.Find(id);
        var studentName = $"{student.FirstMidName} {student.LastName}";  // line 213 - NRE here


```

The code attempts to remove the student and save changes, but the NullReferenceException happens earlier on line 213 when trying to access properties of a null student object. The exception gets caught by the generic Exception handler, which logs the error and redirects to Index with an error message.

However, the real issue is that the catch block itself is throwing another NullReferenceException on line 225 when trying to set TempData["ErrorMessage"]. This happens because TempData isn't properly initialized in the test context since there's no HTTP context set up. I need to mock or initialize the TempData provider to fix this test scenario.

```

csharp
var tempData = new TempDataDictionary(httpContext, tempDataProvider);
controller.TempData = tempData;
```

